Data Import

gwas_height <- fread('phenocode-50.tsv')

Exercise

Part 1 - Data

Lets start by inspecting our data

gwas_height %>% head()
gwas_height %>% dim()
[1] 10894596        9

We see that there is no allele frequency column here. Instead there is an ac (allele count) column. We want to show later on the allele frequency so lets create that column.

gwas_sample_size <- 336474 # from the about tab in the link provided in the pptx
total_allele_count <- gwas_sample_size * 2
gwas_height <- gwas_height %>% mutate(af = ac / total_allele_count)

Now lets check.

gwas_height %>% head()

Also the name of chormosome column can give us headaches later on, so lets change that as well.

gwas_height <- gwas_height %>% rename(chr = '#chrom')

It seems like we have everything we need so we can continue.

gwas_height %>% head()

Get the top loci

gwas_height %>%
  arrange(pval)
topSNV_height <- gwas_height %>% 
    arrange(pval) %>%
    .[1, ]

topSNV_height

Now lets take everything 250kb around it.

SNVs_of_interest_height <- gwas_height %>%
    filter(chr == topSNV_height$chr) %>%
    filter(pos > topSNV_height$pos - 250000 &  pos < topSNV_height$pos + 250000)
SNVs_of_interest_height

Write the top loci out

SNVs_of_interest_height %>% fwrite('topSNV_250kb_height.txt', sep = '\t')

Part 2 - Visualization

Our Base Manhattan Plot

gwas_height %>% manhattan(chr = 'chr', bp = 'pos', p= 'pval', snp = 'rsids', 
                                            main = 'Manhattan Plot - Height', highlight = SNVs_of_interest_height$rsids)

Zoomed in Manhattan Plot

gwas_height %>% 
  filter(chr == topSNV_height$chr) %>%
  manhattan(chr = 'chr', bp = 'pos', p = 'pval', snp = 'rsids', 
            xlim = c(topSNV_height$pos - 1000000, topSNV_height$pos + 1000000),
            main = 'Manhattan Plot - Hypertension', highlight = SNVs_of_interest_height$rsids)

Add the top genes position

Genomic Locations for GDF5 Gene 20:34,021,145-34,042,568

# Define the gene region
gene_start_gdf5 <- 34021145
gene_end_gdf5 <- 34042568 

# Define the range around the top SNP
xlim_start <- topSNV_height$pos - 1000000
xlim_end <- topSNV_height$pos + 1000000

# Create the Manhattan plot data
manhattan_data_height <- gwas_height %>%
  filter(chr == topSNV_height$chr) %>%
  mutate(logp = -log10(pval))

# Create the Manhattan plot with ggplot2
ggplot(manhattan_data_height, aes(x = pos, y = logp)) +
  geom_rect(aes(xmin = gene_start_gdf5, xmax = gene_end_gdf5, ymin = -Inf, ymax = Inf),
            fill = 'palegreen', alpha = 0.2, inherit.aes = FALSE) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.7) +
  scale_color_manual(values = rep("black", length(unique(manhattan_data_height$chr)))) +
  labs(x = paste0('Chromosome ', topSNV_height$chr," position"), y = "-log10(p-value)", title = "Manhattan Plot - Height") +
  theme_minimal() +
  xlim(c(xlim_start, xlim_end)) +
  annotate("text", x = (gene_start_gdf5 + gene_end_gdf5) / 2, y = Inf, label = "GDF5 Gene",
           vjust = 1, hjust = 0.5, color = "darkgreen", size = 5, fontface = "italic")
